Here is a brief summary of how to invoke the LLVM integrated assembler.  For
details, see @ref{Invoking,,Command-Line Options}.

@c Command synopsis

@c We don't use deffn and friends for the following because they seem
@c to be limited to one line for the header.
@example
clang [@b{-a}[@b{cdghlns}][=@var{file}]]
 [@b{--}|@var{files} @dots{}]
@c
@c Target dependent options are listed below.  Keep the list sorted.
@c Add an empty line for separation.

@emph{Target AAP options:}
   [@b{-O}[@var{optimization level}]]

@end example

@c Command options

@table @code

@item -a[cdghlmns]
Turn on listings, in any of a variety of ways:

@table @code
@item -ac
omit false conditionals

@item -ad
omit debugging directives

@item -ag
include general information, like assembler version and options passed

@item -ah
include high-level source

@item -al
include assembly

@item -am
include macro expansions

@item -an
omit forms processing

@item -as
include symbols

@item =file
set the name of the listing file
@end table

You may combine these options; for example, use @samp{-aln} for assembly
listing without forms processing.  The @samp{=file} option, if used, must be
the last one.  By itself, @samp{-a} defaults to @samp{-ahls}.

@item -- | @var{files} @dots{}
Standard input, or source files to assemble.

@end table

@c AAP specific options
The following options are available when the LLVM integrated assembler is
configured for a AAP processor.

@table @code
@item -O @var{otpimization level}
Set the optimization level.

@end table

